# NOETFIELD UNIVERSAL CHANGE-PRESERVATION LAW v1

Applies to every repository, product, website, infrastructure surface, and every coding or automation agent (Cursor, Codex, Claude Code, ChatGPT Work, GitHub Actions, Noetfield Motor workers, future agents).

## CORE INVARIANT

Authorized to implement only the explicitly requested change. Not authorized to reinterpret, replace, clean up, modernize, restore, regenerate, reformat, downgrade, or redeploy unrelated existing work.

Required state transition:

`VERIFIED BASELINE + AUTHORIZED CHANGESET = CANDIDATE STATE`

Do not reconstruct candidate state from whatever local, historical, cached, clean, or convenient snapshot is found.

## MANDATORY PREFLIGHT

Before modifying any file, report:

1. repository name and absolute path
2. current branch
3. local HEAD
4. origin default-branch HEAD
5. working-tree status
6. ahead/behind and ancestry relationship
7. active worktrees and mutation branches
8. current production release SHA or build identifier, when applicable
9. whether live, local, origin, and documented release truth agree
10. exact allowed paths
11. exact protected paths and surfaces
12. whether deployment authority has been granted

If local, origin, intended release, and live state conflict → `BLOCKED_BASELINE_CONFLICT`

If public release contains work not represented by verified Git source → `LIVE_AHEAD_OF_GIT`

Do not overwrite live-ahead work with an older clean commit.

## WORKSPACE RULES

- Do not work directly in the canonical production workspace.
- Use an isolated worktree and isolated branch.
- One mutation lane per repository unless founder explicitly authorizes parallel work.
- Unrelated dirty files are protected existing work — not blockers for isolated scoped work.
- Do not stash, reset, restore, clean, checkout over, reformat, regenerate, stage, commit, or deploy unrelated dirty files.
- Never use "clean HEAD" as proof it is newest or founder-approved.
- Never deploy a full repository from a baseline that excludes newer locked work.

## SCOPE RULES

Before editing, establish a machine-readable task manifest containing:

- verified baseline SHA
- allowed paths
- protected paths
- expected outputs
- forbidden operations
- deployment authority
- merge authority
- locked terminology, routes, capabilities, and public markers

Only files inside the allowlist may change.

Any unexpected changed file → `BLOCKED_SCOPE_BREACH`

Do not silently include, restore, normalize, or explain away unrelated changes.

## PRESERVATION RULES

An update to one component must not reduce, remove, revert, or downgrade any unrelated component.

Require explicit founder authorization for: deletion; route removal; capability removal; content rollback; pricing change; terminology change; shared-layout replacement; configuration replacement; dependency-wide upgrade; generated-output replacement; migration affecting existing data; restoration of an older version; broad visual redesign; cross-repository mutation.

CI and verification must prove:

- changed files ⊆ allowed paths
- protected files remain equivalent to baseline
- locked routes and markers remain present
- no unrelated capabilities disappeared
- candidate history preserves approved ancestry
- generated artifacts do not contain stale surfaces
- public-facing output matches the approved candidate

## AUTHORITY SEPARATION

Builders build. Verifiers verify. Promotion workflows deploy.

Agents may create: isolated branches; scoped changes; tests; commits; pull requests; verification reports; promotion candidates.

Agents may NOT without explicit authority: merge; deploy; force-push; reset; delete branches; rewrite history; modify production redirects; alter credentials; promote a release; select an older release because it is cleaner.

## PRODUCTION RULE

Production deployment requires exact command:

`PROMOTE <SURFACE> <FULL_COMMIT_SHA>`

Deployment workflow must build the exact approved SHA — not local workspace, implicit HEAD, dirty directory, cached artifact, or whichever branch is checked out.

After deployment, verify the real public surface: expected routes; content markers; capabilities; absence of deprecated markers; deployed build/SHA identity; redirects; API behavior where relevant.

A successful provider deployment is not proof that the correct product was released.

## REQUIRED TERMINAL VERDICTS

Use one of these exact verdicts:

- `PASS_SCOPED_CHANGE`
- `BLOCKED_BASELINE_CONFLICT`
- `LIVE_AHEAD_OF_GIT`
- `BLOCKED_SCOPE_BREACH`
- `BLOCKED_PROTECTED_SURFACE_REGRESSION`
- `BLOCKED_NON_DESCENDANT_CANDIDATE`
- `BLOCKED_STALE_RELEASE`
- `BLOCKED_UNAPPROVED_PROMOTION`
- `CANDIDATE_PENDING_FOUNDER_PROMOTION`

Do not claim completion when preservation, release identity, or public verification is unproven.

## WORKER POSTURE

Worker executes or reports blocked. Worker does not accept, acknowledge, ratify, or reinterpret this law.
